data.text:
An engraving of Alessandro Farnese, Duke of Parma and Piacenza (1545–92). Governor of the Spanish Netherlands. Portrait in close ruff and chased armour, with the badge of Golden Fleece on a ribbon. Oval within Latin inscription.

This print is lettered around the portrait: "ALEXANDER FARNESIVS PARMAE ET PLACENTIAE DVX, GUBERN. ET CAPITAN. GENERALIS REGION. BELGICAR."; along the bottom: "Hieronymus Wierix sculp."

The print formed part of an album of portrait prints assembled by Cassiano dal Pozzo in Rome and described in an early nineteenth-century inventory of prints in George III's library as Military Commanders, comprising 143 prints. The album was dismantled later in the nineteenth century and its contents sold during the early twentieth century, when only a few of Cassiano's foreign non-royal portrait prints were retained for the collection.

For more information see Mark McDonald, The Print Collection of Cassiano dal Pozzo. I: Ceremonies, Costumes, Portraits and Genre, 3 vols, Royal Collection Trust 2017, part of The Paper Museum of Cassiano dal Pozzo: A Catalogue Raisonné, cat. no. 1417.
